	<text>
		<body>
			<p><pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB2830_01.jpg"/> The person in question has given us the following information: My <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">father</term> was a joiner, he died 8 years ago. My
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">mother</term>, my older <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">brother</term>, my younger <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">brother</term>, and older <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">sister</term> with her 5-year-old son were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">deported</term> into <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/798544/republic-of-poland.html">Poland</placeName> in <date when="1941-05-15">1941 (the 15th
					May)</date>. When it happened I stayed in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3054643/budapest.html">Budapest</placeName> to
				arrange for the documents needed for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1147" type="subject"
					>citizenship</term>. Three months later my brother managed to come home after a trip full of hardship. Around 70% of the Jews of
				the village were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">deported</term> this time, only the
				widows of soldiers and relatives of labour servicemen remained, the rest were forced to leave the country through the border at
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/688365/yasinya.html">Kőrösmező</placeName>. One time <term type="subject"
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_hungarians">Hungarian</term>, another time <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans"
					>German</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject">soldiers</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-345" type="subject">beat</term> them, elderly people were either <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">shot</term> or thrown into the river <placeName
					ref="#ehri_et_dniester">Dnester</placeName>. They <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532"
					type="subject">shot</term> my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">mother</term> in
				front of my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">brother</term> who managed to come back
				from <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745">death</term>’s door. He was interned for a year
				till his documents arrived but after another year his fate was decided, whe <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-633" type="subject">German occupation</term> brought about another turn in
				the life of Jews. It was now that I got to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3045212/somogyvar.html">Somogyvár</placeName> to my
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">aunt’s</term> place. Naturally, everything
				started also here with wearing the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-339" type="subject">yellow
					star</term>. After a thorough <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-655" type="subject">search</term> on
				the <date when="1941-05-18">18th of May</date> we were carried into the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3044221/tab.html">Tab</placeName> travelling like a caravan of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-670" type="subject">Gipsies</term> as we could carry along quite a lot of
				things. Here they <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-552" type="subject">designated</term> only one street
				for this purpose. This was enclosed, guarded by <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_jewish_police">Jewish policemen</term> inside and
				by <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1125" type="subject">military gendarmes</term> outside. There were
				around 200 Jewish <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819">families</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-546" type="subject">crammed</term> here, 20-30 living in one room, we
				could hardly lie down. We also had a soup kitchen but who had some food supply preferred to cook at home. The members of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-873" type="subject">Jewish Council</term> were <persName
					ref="#ehri_et_weisz">Weisz</persName>,<persName ref="#ehri_et_szirmai">Szirmai</persName>, etc.; we had no complains about them.
				Till the age of 50 everyone had to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> here,
				they took us for agricultural work, for construction works, we built a levente centre. <pb n="2" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB2830_02.jpg"/> The
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-637" type="subject">peasants</term> of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3044221/tab.html">Tab</placeName> did not want the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> to be built there, therefore, debates
				about the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> lasted for long but the
				notary of the community, who was a notorious <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-329" type="subject"
					>antisemite</term>, and had lot of land wanted free Jewish <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556">labour force</term> from the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> but also wanted to show off with the
				levente centre. We were distributed on different estates of the area, we <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> from Monday morning till Saturday
				evening, then we returned to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> by
				cars. We had to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> hard but did not have a
				bad life as <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832">food</term> was very good in all manors.
				However, when we finished the work the owner of the estates <persName ref="#ehri_et_gotzen_gusztav">Dr.Gusztáv Götzen</persName> did
				not pay his Jewish <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556">labourers</term>. No one <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">escaped</term> from the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term>, and I cannot recall the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">death</term> of anyone. The 3rd of July, we received
				the order to pack and the day after we already set off. We could carry 15 kilos of luggage. When we were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-655" type="subject">searched</term> by <term type="subject"
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_hungarians">Hungarian</term> soldiers and by <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1125" type="subject">gendarmes</term> we had to undress nude. My friend
				wanted to save a little jar of <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832">apricot jam</term>
				for her daughter but the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1125" type="subject">gendarme</term> performing
				the search noticed it and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-655" type="subject">seized</term> it, together
				with a ball saying that his son would use it. When they finished searching us they <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">entrained</term> us and took us to the court of the
				army station in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3050616/kaposvar.html">Kaposvár</placeName> where ca. 7,000 people were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-614" type="subject">concentrated</term>. We stayed here for five days till
				we were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">entrained</term>, 90 of us in a <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522">wagon</term>. We got a little water at start but
				almost nothing on <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159">German</term> territories. We had
				a bucket for toilet in the car. Two old <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825">women</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> during the journey, we had their <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-515" type="subject">dead bodies</term> in the car until <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2" type="camp">Birkenau</placeName>. It is quite a miracle that only two
				old <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556">women</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> since the heat was almost unbearable in
				the open <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522">wagons</term>. In <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/724443/kosice.html">Kassa</placeName><term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1125" type="subject">gendarmes</term> got into the wagons and told us to
				have patience and not to commit <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-217" type="subject">suicide</term>, we
				would be carried into <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159">Germany</term> where we would
				live well, there were going to be cinemas and theatres there, we only needed to work. When we arrived in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2" type="camp">Auschwitz-Birkenau</placeName> the third night, we almost
				respired with relief after this awful journey although we did not know what would happen next. <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">Häftlings</term> in striped <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">clothes</term> came up in the wagons and ordered us to
				get off and to leave all our stuff in the car. When we queued up five in each line the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">selected</term> us. We did not know what it was
				about I could not even say goodbye to my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">aunt</term>
				when they took me into the baths, cut my hair, depilated me, and put me under cold shower. We were so weary that I was close to
				feeling well after the shower and did not care about my hair any more. They took our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">clothes</term> and gave us instead <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">blouses</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">long skirts</term> and put a cross in red ink on the
				back. If the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">blouse</term> was thin the ink filtered
				through and ate into the skin. After the bath, I got into <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496"
					type="subject">lager B</term> where we were 800 of us divided in two barracks. There were not even berths here, we <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">sat on the ground</term> cluttered up, lying was out
				of question of course. I stayed here for four weeks, this was the worst barrack, the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">rain constantly fell in</term>. Apart for <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-487" type="subject">roll calls</term> there was nothing to do, this was
				what filled our days. In the morning we got <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">black
					coffee</term>, at 8 am some grass-like <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject"
					>soup</term> which I never tasted during the time I was in <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2"
					type="camp">Auschwitz</placeName>, and in the evening a little piece of bread and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">Zulag</term>. <pb n="3"
					facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB2830_03.jpg"/> The 7th of August, I was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411"
					type="subject">selected</term> for a group meant to <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556">work</term> in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-107" type="camp">Lichteanu</placeName>. The journey took us three days and
				we received sufficient <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">bread</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">sausage</term> for these days. We travelled 60 of us
				in a car and when we arrived to <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-107" type="camp"
					>Lichtenau</placeName> I was very glad we got into a relatively clean <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567">camp</term>. Everyone had a place to sleep, a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">blanket</term>, and even a cup and a spoon, so we
				started to feel like civilised people again. Our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject"
					>job</term> was to fill 18 kilos heavy grenades in the ammunition plant and to help entraining the goods. We had to prepare around
				2,000-2,500 pieces a day rushed by the masters. We <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556"
					>worked</term> 8 hours a day but in some special fields people had to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> 12 hours. Every three weeks we changed
				shift; there were morning, afternoon and night shifts. Some masters beat us but generally all rushed us shouting <q>Los, los.</q> In
					<date when="1944-12">December</date>, there was less <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556"
					type="subject">work</term> to do as we ran out of raw material, hence we were sent for <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">forest work</term>. This was much worse, we walked to
				the mountains in knee-high snow to work with the pickaxe and it was often already 10 pm when we got back to the <foreign xml:lang="de"
					>lager</foreign>. We walked 15 kilometres far away in wooden slippers in which we hardly could walk. <date when="1945-01-15"
					>January the 15th</date>, we started <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556"
					>working</term> again in the plant. We were very happy about it as we stopped having cold even if we had to <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556">work</term> hard. At the end of <date when="1945-03">March</date>,
					<orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004289">Americans</orgName> were getting closer so they hurriedly
				put us on <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">trains</term>, 100 in each freight car,
				and gave us a loaf of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">bread</term> each. We spent
				six days and nights in the cars, the officer who came with us could not decide where to land with us, till we arrived to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2879139/leipzig.html">Leipzig</placeName>, where we got off and spent three weeks in a <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567">camp</term>. <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004289">Americans</orgName> got closer again, so we left <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2879139/leipzig.html">Leipzig</placeName> and walked three weeks by day and night. We slept on the
				fields in the open, in rain and cold, we got every second day some pieces of cooked <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">potatoes</term>, the skilful could obtain some raw
				ones but most importantly we ate the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">sorrel</term>
				of the fields, but we had to suffer even for the sorrel as the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-478"
					type="subject">SS-bitch</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-345" type="subject">beat</term> us if she caught us. A day before the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject">liberation</term> a little girl went into a
				peasant yard to have a rest in the pigpen and therefore was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532"
					type="subject">shot</term>. We did not see <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832"
					>bread</term> during these three weeks. <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004289"
					>Americans</orgName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject">liberated</term> us the <date when="1945-04-27">27th
					of April</date> at <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2805597/wurzen.html">Wurtzen</placeName>, where we stayed in the
				following three weeks and rejoiced in all kinds of good <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832"
					type="subject">food</term> so we made up for the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-570" type="subject"
					>hunger</term> we had before. Three weeks later the <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004583"
					>Russians</orgName>, who arrived here later, entrained us and took us to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3080944/zagan.html">Sagan</placeName> where we stayed in a tolerable <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567">camp</term> for seven weeks. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">ill</term> were cured in <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">hospital</term>. We returned home via <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3070122/nachod.html">Nachod</placeName> with a <term type="subject"
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_czechs">Czech</term> transport. My plans for the future: to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-203" type="subject">emigrate</term> to <placeName ref="#ehri_et_palestine"
					>Palestine</placeName>.</p>
		</body>
